snippet.textDisplay:
Spacial disorientation in mist and fog are a major possibility in this accident.
No identifier lights, strobe or beacon on, in the adverse meteorological conditions according to the reviewed videos is a possible sign of mechanical distress, unknowing of the Pilot and Aircrew in a time frame enough to dial in distress on a radio transponder.
The Skikorsky helicopter does have more than 1 means of distress alert notice to ground, and ENROUTE facilities.
It is known the Skikorsky Helicopter did make multiple communications by UHF radio channels, which pilot and Aircrew can iactivate if an in flight emergency exists.
.The Skikorsky helicopter is equipped with identifier lights and strobe/ beacon lights on the tail, on the top of the fuselage, and on the bottom of the fuselage, which were not on according to the video footage. This could mean an already pre- existing mechanical problem.
A smog, or smog inversion combined with fog, can reduce the air quality which is a large concern in especially major cities to which side effects could take place.
The Skikorsky helicopter has a 200 m.p.h. tested maximum rated airspeed, without modifications.
The Skikorsky helicopter has a maximum 13 person capacity and/ or weight rating, including pilot and co- pilot, other versions exist.
The Skikorsky helicopter uses JP-5 , a turbine fuel, that is highly flammable, according to the video reviewed the fuel load, measured with both a gallons and hours/ minutes guage on board was far from empty with the after landing accident.
T00383087
